citeinfo.title: Vulnerability of Surface-Water Features to Groundwater Pumping

descript.abstract:
These data represent surface water features, derived from the Minnesota DNR's Public Waters Inventory and the US Fish and Wildlife Services' National Wetlands Inventory.
1. PWI basins were intersected with NWI wetlands - the area of each unique wetland type within each basin was calculated. Each basin was then assigned that wetland type which covered the greatest proportion of its extent.
2. Approximate depths were assigned to all wetland types present in the study area. The data were saved in tabular form, and joined to the basins feature class by wetland type - thus an approximate depth was derived for each basin.
3. The basin extents were clipped from the wetlands feature class - wetland fragments less than 60 square meters were then removed, as the basin and wetland edges weren't perfectly coincident, and polygon slivers remained after the clip.
4. The depth table was joined to the wetlands by wetland type, and each wetland was assigned an approximate depth. Adjacent wetlands of the same depth were then dissolved together.
5. Basins and wetlands were merged into a single feature class. An ID was assigned to each wetland, based on the county in which the greatest proportion of the wetland is found.
descript.purpose: These data were developed as an aid in determining the vulnerability of surface-water features to groundwater pumping.

timeperd.current: These data are derived from datasets published May and July 2008.

overview.eaover:
The attribute definitions below apply to both basins and streams unless noted.
** Applies to streams only *Applies to basins only
OBJECTID Internal feature number: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.
Shape Feature geometry: Coordinates defining the features.
*DOWLKNUM DNR Division of Waters Lake
Name DNR Division of Waters Lake Name
Depth Depth of lake or wetland from MN DNR or estimated based on wetland type
Wetland_ID Wetland Identification used for internal processing
Combined_ID Combination of either the DOWLKNUM or wetland ID, with preference given to DOWLKNUM
WT Water table elevation in feet (MSL)
Surf_Elev Ground surface elevation in feet (MSL)
Separation Difference between Bot_Elev and WT (feet). Used to determine connection with groundwater
Bot_Elev Elevation of the bottom of the feature (feet, MSL).
Shape_Length Length of feature in internal units.
Shape_Area Area of feature in internal units squared.
THCK_SCORE LPU Score - Part 2 - Thickness Score
GW_Connection Connection with groundwater Connected: Surface-water features less than five feet above the regional water table surface are generally considered well connected to groundwater. Disconnected: Surface-water features greater than 25 feet above the regional water table are considered to be perched, or disconnected Indeterminate: The connection between groundwater and surface-water features was considered to be indeterminate for surface water features 5 feet to 25 feet above the regional water table
Biota Sensitive Biota (trout streams, calcareous fens)
Vulnerability Potential vulnerability of groundwater pumping
Geo_Data Geology data available
Percent_less_5ft Percent of lake surface area less than 5 feet deep
LPU_Score
Low Permeability Unit Score (SURF_LPU + BDRK_SCORE + THCK_SCORE )
Water_Balance Percent of lake water balance inflow from groundwater
Local_Study Local study vulnerability determination
Vulnerability_Score Vulnerability Score
SIMP_ID Identification number used for internal processing
SURF_LPU LPU Score - Part 1: Connection with Surficial Low Permeability Units
BDRK_SCORE LPU Score - Part 3: Shallow Bedrock Confining Units
**TypeCode Value - Description 1 - "Gaining" 2 - "Losing / Indeterminate" 3 - "Disconnected"
